\begin_layout Subsection
Dynamic pressure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most straightforward application of measurements from the LAMS is to
 predict the dynamic pressure 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is the ambient pressure, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{p}$
\end_inset

 the respective specific heats of air at constant volume or constant pressure,
 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 the absolute temperature, and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{a}$
\end_inset

 the gas constant for air, the Mach number 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 (ratio of flight speed 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 to the speed of sound 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\gamma R_{a}T}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=c_{p}/c_{v}$
\end_inset

) is given by the following equation (cf., e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "NCAR_OpenSky_TECH-NOTE-000-000-000-064"

\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
, which arises from conservation of energy and depends only on the gas behaving
 approximately as a perfect gas [give reference]
\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M=\frac{v}{\sqrt{\gamma R_{a}T}}=\left\{ \left(\frac{2c_{v}}{R_{a}}\right)\left[\left(\frac{p+q}{p}\right)^{R_{a}/c_{p}}-1\right]\right\} ^{1/2}\,\,.\label{eq:MachEq-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solving for the dynamic pressure gives
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q=p\left\{ \left(\frac{v^{2}}{2c_{p}T}+1\right)^{c_{p}/R_{a}}-1\right\} \label{eq:qFromLAMS-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which shows that, with knowledge of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, LAMS (measuring 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

) can provide an independent prediction of the dynamic pressure 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, small errors in 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 will have a small effect on the deduced dynamic pressure because expected
 errors are a small fraction of the total ambient pressure or the absolute
 temperature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Corrections are usually applied to measurements of dynamic pressure on research
 aircraft, including the NSF/NCAR research aircraft, so comparing 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 as provided by (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
